http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/health/11heartweb.html	Electric Pulses, Instead of Shocks, Can Help Heart Patients - New York Times Mental Health & Behavior Electric Pulses, Instead of Shocks, Can Help Heart Patients Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 11, 2007 DENVER, May 10 — Many heart patients who believe that their lives have been saved by shocks from implanted could have survived without a jolt from the devices, according to research presented here today at a meeting of heart specialists. The devices can safely be programmed instead to rely on pacemaking features, which deliver a stream of electric pulses that patients do not feel, in many situations where they currently deliver the shocks, the study concluded. In fact, the data suggested that programming the devices to ignore some irregularities in a patient’s heartbeat and thus to deliver shocks less frequently might actually save lives. The study comes on top of well-known data that 80 percent or more of the patients who receive the defibrillators as protection against a seizure never need a shock. Now, with the new study concluding that even when the devices are thought to be saving lives they might be doing so in an unnecessarily harsh way, doctors are likely to be more worried than ever about their inability to figure out when patients truly need the devices and how best to use them. “A lot of these shocks should be classified as inappropriate,” said Dr. Bruce L. Wilkoff, a defibrillator expert from the Cleveland Clinic Foundation who was the lead investigator and who presented the study results. Commenting on the lower death rate in the group of 700 patients whose devices were programmed to give shocks in fewer situations, Dr. Wilkoff said the difference was not statistically significant enough to ensure that the study’s approach was safer. But the trends in the data raised questions about whether unnecessary shocks weaken hearts in ways that raise the risks of death or hospitalization, he said. The new study was sponsored by Medtronic, the leading manufacturer of implanted defibrillators. It reflected the struggle among doctors to figure out the best uses of the expensive defibrillators. Other studies presented at the meeting explored specialized stress tests and minute differences in the behavior of hearts that might pinpoint which patients are most at risk of sudden cardiac arrest if they do not get defibrillators. The devices, which consist of a pocket-watch-size generator implanted in the chest and one to three leads inserted into the heart, cost as much as $50,000 to implant. Major clinical trials have shown that hundreds of thousands of Americans annually suffer from heart conditions — mainly a sharply reduced capacity to pump blood — that put them at risk for the kinds of breakdowns the defibrillators are designed to manage. Doctors believe that thousands of lives have been saved by the devices and that they should be more widely used. But the inability to figure out which patients are most at risk has slowed growth in the market, which was also hit in 2005 by news of malfunctions linked to a handful of deaths. Guidant, the manufacturer of the deadly devices, compounded the negative reaction by failing to disclose the problems promptly. Not all of the research reported here was weighty. The Heart Rhythm Society, the medical group that runs the annual meeting, also highlighted a small study by a Michigan high school student demonstrating that iPods can disrupt some functions of standard pacemakers when they are placed in a shirt pocket. The biggest impact among the 100 patients tested was a case in which the iPod caused the pacemaker to skip a few beats. Jay Thaker, the 17 year-old student who came up with the idea for the study, worked at with Dr. Krit Jongnarangsin, who has since moved to the The study was the first to focus on portable music players but did not surprise anyone at the meeting because of numerous studies in the past showing that other devices like cell phones have similar effects. Patients who get implants are routinely warned about exposure to a wide range of consumer electronics, airport screening machines and other devices that generate electromagnetic fields. Next Article in Health (2 of 16) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. U.S. Approves Improvements For Implants Defibrillator Maker Props Up Stress Test Company Growing Debate As Doctors Train On New Devices TECHNOLOGY; U.S. Shields Doctor Data In Implants Next Article in Health (2 of 16) &#x00bb; Everything you need to know about heart disease Hip resurfacing: is it right for you? The changing attitudes towards "chemo brain" Treating the awkward years THE NEW YORK TIMES GUIDE TO ESSENTIAL KNOWLEDGE N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
