http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/washington/11fda.html	Passage of Drug Safety Bill Was Common Goal for Two Very Different Senators - New York Times Passage of Drug Safety Bill Was Common Goal for Two Very Different Senators Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 11, 2007 WASHINGTON, May 10 &#151; Legislation to beef up drug safety, passed by the Senate this week with only one dissenting vote, grew out of an extraordinary pact between two senators and a frantic effort by the pharmaceutical industry to avoid any disruption in the approval of new drugs. The bill would increase the fees paid by drug makers to help finance the work of the Food and Drug Administration and would give the agency new power to police company conduct. Industry lobbyists and executives said they supported the bill for one overriding reason: pink slips. Sometime this summer, if a bill has not passed, medical officers at the F.D.A. will start getting notices that they are in danger of being laid off by the end of the fiscal year on Sept. 30. Some of those officers are likely to be in the midst of reviewing new drug applications crucial to the future of drug makers. If those medical officers leave, drug approvals may be delayed &#151; a terrifying prospect for many companies. &#8220;The last thing we want is for F.D.A. employees to start thinking they may not have a job and start leaving,&#8221; said Alan R. Goldhammer, deputy vice president of Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, a trade group for brand-name drug companies. In addition, many in the drug industry said they supported the bill because they believed that it would help restore public confidence in the nation&#8217;s drug supply. &#8220;There has been a loss of confidence in the F.D.A., and we can&#8217;t afford to have that,&#8221; said Dr. Joseph M. Feczko, Pfizer&#8217;s chief medical officer. &#8220;When our medicines come out, we want people to understand they have gone through a rigorous review process.&#8221; Under the bill, the F.D.A. could impose civil fines on companies that violated a drug safety plan or ran false or misleading advertisements. But major drug makers said they would comply with federal requirements, so the agency would not have reason to impose penalties on them. , Democrat of Massachusetts, was chief sponsor of the legislation, but Senator Michael B. Enzi, Republican of Wyoming, was equally responsible for its contents. In an unusual display of bipartisanship, they worked together to fend off amendments that would have made the bill unacceptable to the White House, raised the ire of the pharmaceutical industry or jeopardized chances for passage. &#8220;Kennedy and I have developed a trust,&#8221; Mr. Enzi said in an interview. &#8220;We don&#8217;t try to run over each other. We have a history of passing bills &#151; 27 signed by the president in the last two years.&#8221; An earlier version of the legislation was introduced by Mr. Enzi last August, when controlled Congress and he was chairman of the Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions. When Democrats took control this year and Mr. Kennedy became chairman of the committee, he kept his compact with Mr. Enzi. Working together, they steered the legislation through the committee and the full Senate. Along the way, they accepted dozens of changes proposed by lawmakers of both parties. Mr. Enzi, an accountant and former owner of a shoe store, was mayor of Gillette, Wyo., and served 10 years in the State Legislature. His quiet manner could hardly differ more from that of Mr. Kennedy. Mr. Enzi is as conservative as Mr. Kennedy is liberal. But both are pragmatic legislative craftsmen. Mr. Enzi was recruited into politics by former Senator Alan K. Simpson, another Wyoming Republican who collaborated with Mr. Kennedy on many issues, including In an interview, Mr. Simpson said: &#8220;Mike is a legislator. He&#8217;s calm. He&#8217;s steady. He&#8217;s not a partisan kook or anything of that nature.&#8221; Mr. Simpson said Mr. Enzi and Mr. Kennedy had &#8220;a mutual admiration society, built on trust, respect and friendship, with none of the savage partisanship&#8221; found elsewhere in American politics. Mr. Enzi holds the Senate seat once held by Mr. Simpson and his father, Milward L. Simpson, who entered the Senate on the same day as Mr. Kennedy, Nov. 7, 1962. &#8220;Teddy loved my dad,&#8221; said Mr. Simpson, who nurtured the relationship between Mr. Enzi and Mr. Kennedy. , Republican of New Hampshire, voted against the drug safety bill in the committee, but worked with Mr. Kennedy and Mr. Enzi to make changes that won his support for the legislation on the floor. &#8220;There&#8217;s a Ted Kennedy who is quite flamboyant and partisan in the theater of the Senate,&#8221; Mr. Gregg said in an interview. &#8220;And there is a Ted Kennedy who is extremely bipartisan and willing to work with people in the back rooms of the Senate.&#8221; Industry officials breathed a huge sigh of relief when the Senate approved an amendment offered by Senator Thad Cochran, Republican of Mississippi, that would effectively maintain the current ban on imported drugs. Drug makers fiercely oppose efforts to legalize imports of lower-cost medicines from Canada and other countries. Having won that fight, drug company executives said, they decided not to fight other provisions that they saw as less threatening. &#8220;They need to pick their battles,&#8221; said Barbara Ryan, a pharmaceutical industry analyst at Deutsche Bank Securities. &#8220;Anything that doesn&#8217;t interfere with pricing and approvals is not going to hurt them seriously.&#8221; Still, many advocates, including some who support the bill&#8217;s passage, said the legislation was not the answer to the nation&#8217;s drug safety problems. &#8220;We have horrible leadership at the F.D.A., and they don&#8217;t even use the authorities they already have,&#8221; said Dr. Steven Nissen, chairman of the department of cardiovascular medicine at the Cleveland Clinic. More Articles in Washington &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Senate Vote Upholds Drug Import Limits Court Strikes Law Barring Sale of Drug Data Break Seen In Logjam Over Trade A State's Files Put Doctors' Ties To Drug Makers on Close View More Articles in Washington &#x00bb; The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
